\begin_layout Subsection*
Demand for IVR, SMS reception and Local Average Treatment Effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an encouragement design such as the IVR treatment, households self-select
 into the treatment.
 It may be instructive to look at differences in baseline characteristics
 between households that decide to make use of the IVR system and those
 that do not.
 The first column of Appendix Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Determinants-of-IVR"

\end_inset

 therefore shows the results of an ordinary least squares (OLS) regression
 of an indicator that takes the value of one if the IVR system log showed
 that a household called in at least once using the phone number that was
 recorded during baseline data collection and zero otherwise on various
 baseline variables (and the SMS treatment allocation).
 Results show that none of the baseline characteristics predict demand for
 the IVR service, except for access to a mobile phone.
 We also find the SMS messages seemed to have increased the likelihood that
 farmers called the IVR hotline as intended.
 Even though farmers do not self-select into the SMS treatment, for mostly
 technical reason, the system reported that some messages could not be delivered
 to the intended recipients.
 We therefore ran a similar regression explaining SMS message reception
 by a range of baseline characteristics (second column of Appendix Table
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Determinants-of-IVR"

\end_inset

).
 Unsurprisingly, mobile phone ownership and access are the main determinants
 of SMS reception.
 However, we also find that larger households and households with better
 educated heads were more likely to receive the messages.
 This may be because these households reside in areas that have better network
 coverage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As demand for the IVR service (and to a lesser extent reception of SMS messages)
